Impact of Transmission Type on Fuel Efficiency in MTCARS Data Set

Allen Hammock

June 13, 2015

Executive Summary

To view the code for this report, check out the repository on Github.

At Motor Trend, a magazine about the automobile industry, we are interested in exploring the relationship between a transmission types and fuel efficiency measured in miles per gallon (MPG). We performed a study on 32 different models and found, as a group, that the motorcars with Automatic transmissions had an overall better mean fuel efficiency of 24.4 MPG versus vehicles with Manual transmissions which had an average 17.1 MPG.

However, when we look at cars in different weight classes, we see that the transmission type has a much lower influence on fuel efficiency. The coeffecients on our linear model show, that Manual and Automatic transmissions have approximately the same influence on fuel efficiency (MPG) if we hold the weight constant.

MPG ~ TRANSMISSION TYPE (NO INTERCEPT)

From our initial fit, we can see the expected value for MPG is just the coefficient, or the mean average of the fuel efficiency ratings for each transmission type.

## lm(formula = mpg ~ TransType - 1, data = mtcars)
##   TransTypeAuto TransTypeManual 
##           24.39           17.15

MPG ~ WEIGHT + TRANSMISSION TYPE (NO INTERCEPT)

When we adjust for the weight of the vehicle in addition to the transmission type, we see the difference between Manual and Automatic diminish dramatically.

## lm(formula = mpg ~ wt + TransType - 1, data = mtcars)
##              wt   TransTypeAuto TransTypeManual 
##           -5.35           37.30           37.32

In our analysis below you will see that regression diagnostics support this conclusion. We also examine the leverage that other factors such as the number of cylinders have on the overall fuel efficiency outcome.
